REASONS FOR JUDGMENT

HARTNETT J

PRELIMINARY

In this proceeding, the parties sought competing final property orders. The applicant de facto husband (“the husband”) filed an Initiating Application for Final Orders on 21 November 2023. The first respondent de facto wife (“the wife”) filed a Response to the Initiating Application on 30 November 2023. The matter was transferred to the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia (Division 1) in May 2025. Each of the husband and the wife subsequently filed an amending Initiating Application and Response to Initiating Application in July and August 2025 respectively.
In essence, the husband, and the second, third and fourth respondents, being corporate entities controlled and owned by the husband, argued that there should be no alteration and/or enhancement of the property interests of the wife, and no alteration of the property interests of the parties, beyond that which had already occurred. He submitted that he retains 80 per cent of the current net assets of the parties and the wife has already 20 per cent of those assets. He further submitted that at commencement of cohabitation, the husband owned 95 per cent of the assets then owned by the parties, and the wife owned 5 per cent. In essence, the wife argued that she should retain the property owned by her, and that the husband should pay to her a further sum which represented a 45 per cent overall adjustment in her favour of the current net assets of the parties. The wife also sought spousal maintenance in the sum of $750 each week until such time as any ordered payment had been made to the wife in full, and the plant and equipment of the husband on the wife’s property in City H had been removed from the property by the husband.
The parties commenced their relationship in 2009 and commenced cohabitation in January 2012. They separated over 11 years later, in October 2023, under the one roof. Physical separation occurred in July 2024, when the husband moved out of the wife’s home. The parties do not have any children together. The wife has three adult children with her former partner, and the husband has four adult children from his previous marriage. Neither party remained employed or working at trial, the wife having retired and the husband describing himself as semi-retired.
The dispute centred largely around the parties’ contributions, the husband’s being significant at the commencement of cohabitation. The impact of that superior initial contribution was a significant issue for determination. Additionally, during cohabitation, the husband carried out large works upon the land at the property known as and situate at G Street City H in the State of Victoria (“the [G Street] property”). The G Street property is owned by the wife and is the property in which the parties resided during their de facto relationship. Although these works as carried out by the husband, increased the value of the property by approximately $350,000, the wife asserted that the works have caused damage to the land which will cost a significant amount to rectify. There was before the Court no expert evidence as to the need for rectification works, nor any expert evidence as to the costs of any rectification works.
At the time of trial, there remained plant and equipment as belonging to the husband, on the property of the wife. The wife wanted its removal from the property as carried out by the husband or his agent. By trial, this mostly heavy industrial machinery remained on the wife’s property, with the husband having no plans for its imminent removal. Counsel for the wife described the scene as an “industrial dump”, the presence of which was “overwhelming” to the wife who had long sought its removal.

Orders Sought

In his Amended Initiating Application filed 28 July 2025, the husband sought the following final orders:
The Respondent Wife ("the Wife") retain the Payment received from the Applicant Husband ("the Husband") in the sum of $100,000 (First Payment).
The Wife retain all assets in her name and/or control including but not limited to:
[G Street], [City H], Victoria [...] (Volume [...] Folio [...] ([City H] Property)):
[R Street], [City H], Victoria [...] (Volume [...] Folio [...]) ([R Street] Property);
c. Any motor vehicles registered in her name;

d. Any Superannuation in her name; and

e. Any bank accounts in her sole name.
The Husband retain all assets in his name and/or control and all assets in the name of and/or control of the 2nd, 3rd and 4th Respondents, being the following corporate entity:
Bank accounts in his sole name or the name of the 2nd 3rd and 4th Respondents.

b. [P Street] [Town Q], Victoria (Volume [...] Folio [...]):
Property situate at [Remote Location N], [Region O], Tasmania (Volume [...] Folio [...]): and

d. [B Pty Ltd] (ACN [...]) ATF
i. [K Trust]: and

ii. [Guttenberg Trust];
Including the assets of [B Pty Ltd] and both Trusts as follows:
[J Street]. [Suburb M], Victoria [...] (Volume [...] Folio [...], Volume [...] Folio [...], and Volume [...] Folio [...]):
[1 L Street], [Suburb M], Victoria [...] (Volume [...] Folio [...]);
[C Pty Ltd] (ACN [...]) and all remaining sale proceeds upon the settlement by the Mortgagee in Possession of the property situate at [E Street]. [Suburb F] Victoria [...] (Volume [...] Folio [...]):
[D Pty Ltd] (ACN [...]) and to include all plant, machinery and motor vehicles registered in the Husband's name, or any of the corporate entities of which he is an officeholder or shareholder, being the plant, machinery and motor vehicles particularised in the valuation prepared by All­ Asset Appraisals;
g. [T Pty Ltd] (ACN [...]):

h. [U Pty Ltd] (ACN [...]):

i. [V Pty Ltd] (ACN [...]):
Any other company. trust. business or entity controlled by the Applicant, or the 2nd 3rd and Respondents.

k. Other personal assets and possessions as follows:
i. His wine collection;

ii. [Dining table];
All other items of machinery. tools and equipment brought by him to the [G Street] property and any other building materials and assets that he brought to that property or were purchased by him or the 2nd 3rd or 4th respondents during the relationship, that are not fixed by concrete, bolt or nail.
The Husband be permitted to store on the [G Street] property the plant and equipment defined and particularised in the [FF Pty Ltd] Valuation. and all other plant and equipment required for the operation of his businesses and any other plant and equipment for any other future business he undertakes pending the sale of the [Suburb F] Property until December 2026.
The upon the settlement of the [E Street] sale (due [February 2026]; the sale proceeds shall be distributed as follows:
To discharge the Mortgage to [GG Limited]. and pay all marking. selling, legal and other costs associated with the mortgagee sale;
Pay all outstanding. rates, taxes and any other encumbrance, include land tax for the [E Street] Property;
Pay any other outstanding rates taxes and body corporate fees for the properties owned by [B Pty Ltd];
An amount of $51,561 be placed in the trust account of the husband's solicitor to pay CGT as and when raised, and once that CGT has been assessed and/or paid;
Such amounts as required to discharge the Supreme Court Cost Order: and
f. The balance be retained by the Applicant.
The Husband assume sole responsibility for any loan or liability in his name or the 2nd 3rd and 4th Respondents encumbering or associated with any item of property, real property. company or trust assets, to which he is entitled pursuant to this agreement. and my client indemnify the Wife and keep her indemnified in respect of any liability arising from the Husband's Debts.
The wife assume sole responsibility for any loan or liability in her name and any liability encumbering or associated with any item of property to which she is entitled pursuant to this agreement, and your client indemnify the Husband and keep him indemnified in respect of any liability arising from the Wife’s debts.
In the event that the Wife is to retain any chattel or asset of which the 4th Respondent is the legal owner, being those assets listed and valued in the [FF Pty Ltd] Valuation dated 14 June 2024, then the value of such assets is to be attributed and accounted to the wife’s keep.
9. Such further or other orders as this Honourable Court deems appropriate.
In her Further Amended Response to Initiating Application, filed 1 August 2025, the wife sought the following orders:
The Applicant, Second to Fourth Respondents will pay to the First Respondent an amount representing 45% of the net asset pool available to the parties less $1,400,000 being the value of the First Respondent’s properties at [G Street] and [R Street], [City H], Victoria [...] (“[City H] Property”), in accordance with paragraphs 2 to 9 (“Payment”).
The net proceeds of the mortgagee sale of [E Street], [Suburb F] Victoria [...] being the land contained in duplicate Certificate of Title Volume [...] Folio [...] (“[Suburb F] Property”) and such further amount that represents the Payment is to be paid to the First Respondent.
In the event that the net proceeds of sale of the [Suburb F] Property does not represent the Payment, then the Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents shall pay to the First Respondent, such further amounts required to make the Payment within 60 days of the settlement of the sale of the [Suburb F Property].
Default
In the event that the Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents do not comply with Orders 1 to 3 and/or 14, the parties shall forthwith do all acts and things and sign all documents necessary so as to effect a sale of the following properties:
[J Street], [Suburb M], Victoria [...], being the land contained in [1 J Street] [2 J Street] [5 J Street]; and
[1 L Street], [Suburb M], Victoria [...] being the land contained in duplicate Certificate of Title Volume [...] Folio [...].
(together known as the “[Suburb M] Properties”)
The selling agent acting for the sale of the [Suburb M] Properties be agreed between the parties. Failing agreement, the First Respondent shall nominate three agents and the Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents shall select one of these within 7 days (“Agent”).
The legal practitioner or conveyancer acting for the sale of the [Suburb M] Properties be agreed between the parties. Failing agreement, the First Respondent shall nominate three proposed legal practitioners or conveyancers, and the Applicant select one of these to be legal practitioner or conveyancer within 7 days (“the Conveyancer”).
7. The sale must be conducted as follows:
The parties must do all such acts and things and sign all documents necessary to effect the sale including co-operating with any reasonable request of the Agent;
Each party is at liberty to communicate directly with the Agent and the Conveyancer in relation to the sale, but must provide joint instructions to the Agent and the Conveyancer;
The [Suburb M] Properties are to be sold by private sale or auction, to be agreed between the parties in consultation with the Agent and failing agreement, the method of sale shall be as recommended by the Agent;
The terms of sale and list price / reserve price be as agreed between the parties in consultation with the Agent and failing agreement, the list price / reserve price shall be recommended by the Agent upon written evidence of recent sale prices for properties similar to the [Suburb M] Properties (“the Reserve Price”)
The sale price shall be such amount as is agreed between the parties in writing and failing agreement, any offer to buy the [Suburb M] Properties that is the Reserve Price or above shall be accepted by the parties as a sale price;
In the event the bidding at the auction does not reach the Reserve Price, the parties may negotiate with the highest bidder or any other interested person and effect a sale of the [Suburb M] Properties;
If the [Suburb M] Properties is not sold at auction, then the parties shall do all acts and things and sign all documents necessary to relist the [Suburb M] Properties for the sale by public auction or private sale on such terms as agreed in writing by the parties;
Settlement of the sale is to occur within 90 days of the contract of sale being signed;
Upon agreement being reached for the sale of the [Suburb M] Properties, the Applicant and the Second Respondent shall execute the contract of sale and all other documents necessary to complete the sale of the [Suburb M] Properties including all transfer / PEXA documentation forthwith upon its submissions to them by the selling agent or the conveyancer;
The Applicant and Second to Fourth Respondents shall do all things to maintain the [Suburb M] Properties in the saleable condition and ensure the proper conduct of the marketing and sale; and
Liberty be reserved to both parties to apply to the Court with respect to the terms and conditions of the sale and for further directions in the event that it proves necessary.

8. That pending the sale and settlement of the [Suburb M] Properties:
The Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents pay all outgoings for the [Suburb M] Properties;
The Second Respondent be and are hereby restrained from doing any act or thing which will have the effect of charging, mortgaging or otherwise encumbering or further encumbering the [Suburb M] Properties.
Upon settlement of the sale of the [Suburb M] Properties, the proceeds of sale be applied as follows:
Firstly, to pay all Agent’s costs and expenses relating to the sale, including conveyancing costs, marketing, council, water rates, land tax in respect of the [Suburb M] Properties;

b. Secondly, to pay the balance of the Payment to the First Respondent;

c. The balance as directed by the Applicant.

Withdrawal of Caveats
The First Respondent shall provide a withdrawal of caveat over the [Suburb F] Property at settlement so as to allow the settlement of the mortgagee sale of the [Suburb F] Property.
Contemporaneously with the Payment being made in full to the First Respondent, the First Respondent shall provide a withdrawal of caveat over the [Suburb M] Properties.

[City H] Property
Within 30 days hereof, the Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents must at their sole cost and expense, remove all their possessions (including but not limited to waste material and garden material) and plant and equipment (“Possessions”) from the [City H] Property and make good any damage caused by them due to the removal of the Possessions.
The 3 x [site offices] being 1 x 12 metre length and 2 x 4 metre length are to remain at the [City H] Property.

Spousal Maintenance
Commencing from the date of this Order, the Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents pay the First Respondent periodic spousal maintenance in the amount of $750 per week until such time the Payment has been made to the First Respondent in full and the Possessions have been removed from the [City H] Property in accordance with paragraph 12.

Indemnity and Release

15. The Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents are restrained from:
recording in any tax returns of the Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents any distributions to the First Respondent; and
amending any tax returns previously filed with the Australian Taxation Office for the Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents such as to cause a taxation liability to the First Respondent;
without the First Respondent’s prior written consent.
The Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents pay and indemnify the First Respondent and keep the First Respondent indemnified with respect to:
All payments and liabilities of the First Respondent and/or the parties jointly pursuant to any or all loans, overdraft facilities, hire purchase, lease agreements or personal guarantees entered into by the First Respondent and/or the parties jointly in respect of the Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents;
All liabilities and creditors of whatsoever nature of the Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents, including but not limited to, any liability for income tax, capital gains tax or such other tax (whether past, present or future) howsoever arising;
All income tax payable by the First Respondent in respect of any income distributed or purportedly distributed to her by the Second to Fourth Respondents;
All income tax payable by the First Respondent in respect of the Payment;
Any fringe benefits tax, capital gains tax, goods and services tax and/or any other tax payable by the First Respondent in respect of any income of or from the Second to Fourth Respondents and/or the transfer of any assets, income or entitlements to either of the parties pursuant to these orders by the Second to Fourth Respondents;
Any and all liability of the Applicant and Second to Fourth Respondents to any person, the parties or either of them including any liability pursuant to any loan accounts; and
Any and all liability of the First Respondent pursuant to any loan to or from the Applicant and Second to Fourth Respondents and any taxation liability that arises upon the First Respondent being released from any such liability or arising on account of the implementation of these Orders (whether past, present, or future).
The Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents release and discharge the First Respondent from any / or all claims that any of them may have against her including but not limited to seeking reimbursement to the Applicant of the First Respondent’s half share of the valuations and mediation costs as contained in the following orders:
Paragraph No. 3 of the Order dated 19 May 2025 before the Honourable Justice Hartnett;
Paragraph No. 3 in the Order dated 20 February 2025 before Judge A Humphreys;
Paragraph No. 2 in the Order dated 14 November 2024 before Chief Judge Alstergren; and
Paragraphs 4 and 9 in the Order dated 3 April 2024 before Judicial Registrar Watson.
The Applicant and the Second to Fourth Respondents will not bring any action in any Court or Tribunal against the First Respondent.
Other Assets and Liabilities
Unless otherwise specified in these Orders and save for the purpose of enforcing these Orders
each party shall be solely liable for and indemnify the other party in relation to all property (including choses in action) in his / her own name or in his / her possession as at the date of these Orders;
the Applicant and, the Second to Fourth Respondents shall be solely liable for and indemnify the First Respondent against any liability encumbering any item of property to which the Applicant and the, Second to Fourth Respondents are entitled pursuant to these orders and/or any such liability in the name or control of the Applicant and the, Second to Fourth Respondents, past, present and future;
the First Respondent shall be solely liable for and indemnify the Applicant against any liability encumbering any item of property to which the First Respondent is entitled pursuant to these orders and/or any such liability in the First Respondent’s name, past, present and future;
each party be solely entitled to the exclusion of the other to all other property (including choses-in-action) in the possession of the party as at the date of these Orders.

20. It is agreed that the following assets are to be retained by the Applicant:
monies standing to his credit in any bank, building society or investment accounts held in his sole name;
b. all furniture, contents and personal property in his possession;
[Remote Location N] , [Region O], Tasmania and contained in duplicate Certificate of Title Volume [...] Folio [...];

d. [P Street], [Town Q], Victoria [...];
Subject always to paragraphs 4 to 9 of these Orders, the [Suburb M] Properties;
21. It is agreed that the following assets are to be retained by the First Respondent:
[G Street], [City H], Victoria [...] and described in duplicate Certificate of Title Volume [...] Folio [...];
[R Street], [City H], Victoria [...] and described in duplicate Certificate of Title [...] Folio [...].
monies standing to her credit in any bank, building society or investment accounts held in her sole name, which includes any part property settlement payments made by the Applicant to the First Respondent;
d. all furniture, contents and personal property in her possession;
her superannuation entitlements in [Super Fund 1] Member Number [...];
[Motor Vehicle 1] (registration number [...]);

g. Ride on Mower

h. her [ATV]; and

i. [S Company] Shares.;
Unless otherwise specified in these Orders and save for the purposes of enforcing monies due under these or any subsequent Orders:

a. insurance policies remain the sole property of the named owner;
any joint tenancy of the parties in any real or personal estate is hereby expressly severed;
each party foregoes any claim they may have had to any gifts, inheritances, redundancies or windfall gains to which the other party is entitled, either presently or in the future;
any stamp duty, capital gains tax or other liability that becomes payable as a consequence of these Orders shall be payable by the party receiving the property or benefit from the relevant transaction; and
each party be solely liable for and indemnify the other against any liability of whatsoever nature and kind in their respective names, including but not limited to any tax liability and credit card liability.
Registrar to sign

23. Pursuant to 106A of the Family Law Act 1975:
the Registrar or Deputy Registrar of the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia, Melbourne Registry is appointed to execute all deeds and or instruments in the name of the party in default and do all acts and things necessary to give validity and operation to these orders;
the defaulting party is ordered to pay all reasonable costs incurred by the other party for the purposes of enforcing this order; and
for the purposes of this order, an affidavit setting out the defaulting party’s failure to comply with the orders shall be sufficient evidence of default.

Finalisation

24. No order as to costs between the parties.
Pursuant s 81 of the Family Law Act (1975) (Cth) the parties intend that these orders shall as far as practicable finally determine all financial relationships, both property and spousal maintenance between them.

...

MATERIAL RELIED UPON

The husband and the second, third and fourth respondents relied upon:
(1) the husband’s Amended Initiating Application filed 28 July 2025;

(2) the husband’s affidavits filed 28 July 2025 and 6 August 2025;

(3) the husband’s financial statement filed 28 July 2025;

(4) the affidavit of Ms W, accountant, filed 28 July 2025; and

(5) the husband’s Outline of Case filed 7 August 2025.

The wife relied upon:
(1) her Further Amended Response filed 1 August 2025;

(2) her affidavits filed 30 November 2023, 25 July 2024, 13 August 2024 and 1 August 2025; and

(3) her financial statement filed 1 August 2025; and the affidavit of Steven Kincaid filed 1 October 2024.

All parties relied upon the affidavits of the single expert property valuers, James Dennis and John McEntee, filed 28 July 2025 and 29 July 2025 respectively. Mr Dennis valued the following real properties:
(a) G Street, City H, including a retrospective valuation as of January 2012; the current market value as of 12 July 2025 if the husband had conducted no works; and the current market value on an ‘as is’ basis;

(b) R Street, City H, Victoria, (“the [R Street] Property”) being a current valuation only; and

(c) P Street, Town Q, Victoria, (“the [Town Q] property”) being a current valuation only.

Mr McEntee valued the following real properties:
(a) J Street, Suburb M, Victoria, including a retrospective value as of 1 January 2012; and a current value as of 15 July 2025;

(b) 1 L Street Suburb M, Victoria, including a retrospective value as of 1 January 2012; and a current value as of 15 July 2025; and

(c) E Street, Suburb F Victoria, being a retrospective value only as at l January 2012.

The evidence of the single expert property valuers, both as to the current value of real properties, and any retrospective value of real properties, was not challenged by the parties and such valuations were agreed.
The retrospective valuations, as of 1 January 2012, were as follows:
(a) J Street, Suburb M had a value of $3,600,000;

(b) 1 L Street, Suburb M had a value of $610,000; and

(c) E Street, Suburb F had a value of $3,300,000; and G Street City H had a value of $500,000.

The market value of G Street City H as of 12 July 2025 if the husband had carried out no works was $900,000.

SOME RELEVANT FACTS

In 1946, the husband was born. He was 78 years of age at the time of the trial. He resides in Town Q in property owned by him, and is not now engaged in work, although he is hopeful of a return to working in his own business.
In 1948, the wife was born. She was 77 years of age at the time of trial. She resides in City H in property owned by her and being the property the parties resided in during their de facto relationship. She is retired.
In 1969, the wife had commenced working as a healthcare professional. She continued to be so employed until 2017, some five years after cohabitation commenced. Her work was full-time and then part-time from about 2014, the wife working initially 27 hours per week. In her last year of income, the wife earnt only $7,155, having further reduced her working hours as her administrative work (on behalf of the husband) and farm tasks increased.
In early 1980, T Pty Ltd was incorporated, and the husband became the sole director and shareholder. This company was the husband’s main business. Its profits and income, and significant loans, enabled the husband to purchase most of his various properties.
In mid-1986, U Pty Ltd was incorporated. The husband is the sole director, secretary and shareholder of U Pty Ltd. U Pty Ltd no longer trades.
In mid-1992, X Pty Ltd was incorporated, with the husband, and his former wife, Ms Y, as directors and equal shareholders. X Pty Ltd operates a business known, or previously known as, Z Company. X Pty Ltd is the trustee of the Guttenberg Trust.
In early 1993, B Pty Ltd was incorporated. The husband became the sole director and shareholder.
In April 1993, the Guttenberg Trust was established, of which the husband is the sole appointor. B Pty Ltd is the trustee. The Guttenberg Trust owned 70 per cent of the business of the husband on the husband’s evidence.
In 1995, the wife and her former partner, Mr AA, purchased a property situate at G Street City H (“the [G Street] property”).
In August 2001, K Trust was established, with the husband as the sole appointor and B Pty Ltd as the trustee. K Trust owned the remaining 30 per cent of the husband’s business on the husband’s evidence.
In August 2001, the husband’s former wife, Ms Y, resigned as a director of X Pty Ltd, and transferred her shareholding to the husband, so that he held all 12 shares. The husband became the sole director.
Around 2001, B Pty Ltd purchased L Street, Suburb M (“the [L Street] property”). The husband provided no evidence as to any mortgages taken out by him with respect to the purchase of this property, nor as to when any such mortgages may have been discharged. Nor did he assert the property was purchased unencumbered.
Between the purchase of the L Street property and February 2008, the husband subdivided this property into two lots, being 4 J Street and 5 L Street. Between purchase and February 2008, the husband further subdivided 4 J Street, one part becoming 2 L Street, Suburb M. 2 L Street was purchased by B Pty Ltd in February 2008 and used as the offices of T Pty Ltd and X Pty Ltd. In January 2021, 2 L Street was sold by the husband for $910,000 plus GST. The property had been mortgaged to the Commonwealth Bank of Australia in May 2009, with that mortgage only being discharged at the settlement of the sale of the property in January 2021, being 12 years later, a further encumbrance not disclosed by the husband. The quantum of the mortgage paid during the cohabitation years of 2012 to 2021, being the sale year, are unknown. The net proceeds of sale were ultimately retained by the husband’s lawyers for legal costs incurred by him. 5 L Street was sold as described in [64] below, with no or little monies being received by the husband, noting his evidence was both that the net proceeds were applied solely to legal costs then outstanding with BB Lawyers; and that the net proceeds were applied to those legal fees and to improvements to the G Street property, although he claimed his legal fees were in excess of $3 million being the net sale proceeds obtained by him. Further, although the L Street property was owned by the husband through one of his entities at the commencement of cohabitation, it was only 2 L Street , and 1 L Street (a further subdivision as described hereafter) that the husband claimed as initial contributions. He had lost the balance of the property sale proceeds to the payment of costs.
In October 2001, J Street, Suburb M (“the [J Street] property”) was purchased by B Pty Ltd. This property comprised three titles. 1 J Street, 2 J Street and 3 J Street. Those three titles were each mortgaged to Westpac Banking Corporation from October 2001, with those mortgages being not discharged until July 2017, on the evidence of the wife, which I accept. That discharge occurred five years after cohabitation had commenced. The husband again provided no evidence as to any mortgages taken out by him on purchase nor as to when such mortgages were paid out. The wife calculated at [155] of her affidavit filed 1 August 2025, from financial documents of the husband, that the borrowings on the purchase were approximately $1,300,075, making a net equity in the properties of $2,299,926. It is probable that was the case given that was the best evidence available to the Court. In February 2018, the husband subdivided the J Street property by subdividing 3 J Street into two titles, 4 J Street and 4 L Street, Suburb M. B Pty Ltd became the registered proprietor of the subdivided properties. The husband provided no evidence as to the costs of the sub-division or how it was funded. This occurred during cohabitation. In November 2023, a further subdivision of the remaining J Street property (4 J Street) was approved, and new titles issued, namely 5 J Street and 1 L Street, Suburb M. B Pty Ltd became the owner of 1 L Street.
In about 2004, the husband gifted 50 per cent of X Pty Ltd to his adult children, Mr CC, Mr DD and Ms EE, in equal shares of one sixth each. The husband retained ownership of the remaining half of the shareholding in the entity.
In the second half of 2004, C Pty Ltd and D Pty Ltd were incorporated. The husband is the sole director and shareholder of both entities. D Pty Ltd is the owner of the plant and machinery used by the husband and valued in a joint valuation undertaken by FF Pty Ltd for the purposes of the trial. Those assets were valued at $571,000 in 2025. They included Motor Vehicle 2, registration number [...], a vehicle driven by the wife since 2019. Motor Vehicle 2 had a value of $8,000 to $10,000. That valuation also included a prime mover which was valued at $12,000. Those vehicles, as described hereafter, no longer had any value at trial. The wife damaged Motor Vehicle 2, and it is probable that the costs of repairs needed to the vehicle would exceed the value of the vehicle. The prime mover was written off by a third party and was not insured.
In late 2005, the wife became the sole registered proprietor of the G Street property following a property settlement with her previous partner from whom she had separated in 2002. The G Street property was valued at $400,000 at the time of the transfer of the property to the wife. The wife was required to obtain a $135,000 mortgage to buy out her partner. This mortgage was paid down by the wife, for the most part, prior to the cohabitation of the parties in 2012, and discharged by the wife in July 2013, using her superannuation funds as acquired prior to cohabitation.
In late 2007, C Pty Ltd purchased E Street, Suburb F (“the [Suburb F] Property”) for a purchase price $1.8 million. The property was mortgaged to Westpac Banking Corporation on the transfer date of 22 November 2007, with this mortgage not being discharged until 23 January 2020. Again, there was no evidence before the Court as to the existence of this mortgage, and/or its quantum, as emanating from the husband. The husband thereafter wanted to obtain both refinancing, and further borrowings. He was able to arrange that funding through GG Limited, that entity advancing a sum of $6 million as secured by a mortgage over the Suburb F Property. On 21 October 2021, the Suburb F Property was mortgaged to GG Limited. The reasons for that refinancing included the husband’s desire to construct a factory on the J Street property, and to divide 4 J Street of the J Street property so that a part would become 3 L Street. Additionally, part of those borrowed funds was used to pay various accounts owing for each of the entities, and to be used toward the repayment of the loan repayments to GG Limited, which at that time were approximately $53,232 per month.
In 2007 or 2008, the husband’s first marriage to Ms Y broke down. Following their separation, and with significant contractual pressures from a contract the husband had then with HH Limited, which was not proceeding well, the husband suffered a mental health breakdown. The husband provided no evidence as to any settlement terms between the husband and Ms Y in their respective property proceedings which followed. Importantly, evidence as to what, if any, diminution, by virtue of further borrowings obtained by the husband to pay out Ms Y, in his net equity in the assets he claimed as initial contributions in this proceeding.
In February 2009, the parties met again, they having first met in the 1980s. They commenced a relationship shortly after meeting in 2009. At the time of commencing their relationship, the husband was working in Town JJ, Western Australia, for HH Limited (through T Pty Ltd). This project had cost him money and time, the husband having to spend about two years cleaning up the site on which he worked. The wife was working as a healthcare professional, both at KK Company and LL Company.
When the parties commenced their relationship, the husband told the wife of his bipolar psychiatric diagnosis as well as his depression and other health issues. The wife felt capable of caring for any special needs the husband had in relation to his health condition, given her occupation. The husband conceded that the wife looked after his health needs competently, which included ensuring that the husband took medication for his bipolar disorder.
In 2009, the wife’s G Street property was burnt. The wife’s house, which was situate on only a part of the property, was not burnt down, but the forest area on that property, as well as some fencing, were burnt out in the bush fires.
From approximately 2011 onwards, the husband commenced to move his plant and equipment from the Suburb F Property to the G Street property. The husband deposed that, at that time, the G Street property was a small non-working farm of approximately 190 acres. On the wife’s evidence, which I accept, the farm is 92 acres. The husband used a part of the property as his industrial storage site thereafter, and continuing. The husband further transferred materials from the Suburb F Property, after its sale in February 2025.
In early 2012, the parties commenced co-habitation at the G Street property. The wife’s adult daughter Ms MM and the wife’s sister Ms NN (at times) lived with the parties. They both made some limited contributions to the household expenses of the parties. The wife’s sister Ms NN lived, when not in Western Australia, in a self-contained independent person’s unit, which she built on the property at her own expense, in or about 2011.
Upon moving in, the husband immediately undertook significant earthworks on the G Street property, including deep cuts into the land, to flatten the land. This extensive flat plateau was developed specifically to store the husband’s trucks, machinery and other assets. The bulk of the rocks came from the excavations carried out on the property. Some of the rocks came from OO Centre which the husband demolished.
The husband demolished the wife’s two small sheds, that were adequate for her needs and instead built a massive shed for the wife’s storage of her machinery, and animal food, and, significantly, for the storage of his equipment. He subsequently built a further massive shed for his needs, and a two-storey building for the accommodation of workers employed by him between 2013 and 2015. These works were undertaken without consulting the wife in advance nor gaining her consent.
In 2012, the wife commenced providing some administrative assistance to the husband in the operation of his entities.
In 2012, the husband’s son Mr DD, took over, from the husband, as manager of X Pty Ltd. Mr DD had previously worked for T Pty Ltd.
In 2012, the wife’s wood, as chopped up by the husband, was sold by the parties and by X Pty Ltd. X Pty Ltd retained some of the proceeds and provided other of the proceeds to the parties. The parties kept those monies as received by them and otherwise had a wood supply until the husband left the property.
In 2013, T Pty Ltd had a dispute as to a costs bill of $1,100,00 with its solicitors, PP Lawyers. PP Lawyers had acted on behalf of T Pty Ltd on its various Western Australian litigations, including with HH Limited. The PP Lawyers dispute ultimately resulted in two Supreme Court proceedings, in both 2015 and 2017 which the wife actively managed on behalf of the husband, contributing also to the husband’s exchanges with his solicitors, BB Lawyers. Ultimately, no monies were paid by T Pty Ltd to PP Lawyers. T Pty Ltd had to meet the payment of their own legal costs.
On 23 July 2013, the wife paid off her mortgage loan over the G Street property in the remaining amount of $29,248.49 by drawing down on her superannuation. The mortgage was subsequently discharged.
Between 2011 and 2014, the husband’s QQ Street, Suburb M property (“the [QQ Street] property”), in which the husband had been residing before moving to the wife’s G Street property, was subdivided by him at a cost to the husband of $1,500,000 on his evidence. The property had comprised a house lot (the house demolished the house) and two vacant lots. The husband subdivided the property into 19 house lots. The QQ Street property sold for approximately $6,372,000 in about 2014. After the payment of the costs of sale, taxes, mortgages outstanding to Westpac and the Commonwealth Banks, the balance remaining of $1,211,026.59 was paid to the husband in about 2014. The QQ Street properties were owned by D Pty Ltd as trustee for QQ Trust. The husband claimed that he applied the net sale proceeds to the expenses of his corporate entities and to the payment out of all his mortgages. That latter claim was not made out, the husband having then existing, ongoing mortgages after 2014.
The husband asserted that in the years he cohabitated with the wife, he spent approximately $3,000,000 improving the G Street property, including developing approximately 50 acres of the farmland at his sole expense. There is no dispute that he carried out various works on the property. He provided no probative evidence however, as to his claimed expenditure, and it is probable on the totality of the facts of this case, that he did not spend this sum, nor anything approaching this sum. The valuation of the property, when including the works done by the husband, valued the improvements made in the sum of $350,000.
The works carried out by the husband, as claimed by him in itemised detail in his evidence, and as responded to by the wife, and set out here because of the dispute between the parties as to the value of the works and need for rectification, included:
(a) Removal of the bushfire damaged trees, as conceded by the wife.

(b) Installing ring lock fencing to approximately 40 acres of farmland. The wife conceded that the husband had installed the fencing, but challenged the 40 acres coverage, and stated that the ring lock fencing was around 21 acres, not 40. Further, the wife considered this work unnecessary, as “[RR Organisation]” had replaced all the fencing at the G Street property in 2009. The ring lock fencing was installed by the husband in or about October 2015, because the goats (as wanted and purchased by the husband only) had escaped the paddock and damaged the orchard. The husband then installed the fencing for the purposes of containing the animals (goats, sheep, pigs) that the husband had brought onto the property.

(c) Creating and building seven roads, that provided several kilometres of road access on the farming part of the property. The wife did not accept the evidence of the husband in its entirety but conceded the husband put in four roads on the property, and that the length of the roads was perhaps two kilometres, possibly more. The wife deposed further, that the roads on the property were already in good condition prior to the parties’ relationship. Her evidence was that some roads were subsequently damaged, due to the husband’s heavy trucks and machinery transversing them, which was exacerbated by the unauthorised earthworks as carried out by the husband. The machinery created tracks on the gravel roads, which were washed out by the rain, causing ridges and rocky holes. The husband did repair the roads as claimed by him, but it was the wife’s evidence that they were not compacted properly (he did not have a roller) resulting in the gravel roads being washed out again. When the husband was serving his jail sentence, as referred to hereafter, the roads required urgent attention, which I accept, and accordingly, the wife arranged for a local contractor, SS Pty Ltd, to finally repair the roads properly.

(d) Installing 2000 tons of bluestone rock walls and steel and timber retaining walls as conceded by the wife.

(e) Installing a six megalitre pond (which contained 4000 fish) – what the husband referred to as a ‘house dam’ as conceded by the wife who thought the works “wonderful”, although she did not request them.

(f) Installing an entertainment building situated in the house dam on a six-meter-high pipe filled with concrete with a bridge from shore building to building which included a fireplace, electricity and internet, as conceded by the wife who thought the works “wonderful”, although again she did not request the works and was not consulted with respect to these works being carried out.

(g) Installing two major drains including pits, as conceded by the wife, her evidence being that the husband had installed multiple drains across the property. The wife’s evidence as to these two major drains, was that one collected water from a gully to the north of the property, which was then funnelled into the house dam. The second drain of approximately 210 meters carried the rainwater overflow from the house ham to the back dam, under the 1.3 acre plateau the husband had excavated. The plateau has seven points of access to the main drain. The wife deposed that five of these points required urgent attention at the time of the trial, as they were exposed drains with broken, inadequate covers, and were dangerous. The plateau was flooded with water pouring out of the drain points during the October 2022 flooding event, as referred to hereafter. Some excess soil from the excavation to create the plateau was used to raise the bank of the back dam. In doing so, the wife claimed that the husband altered the original drainage from the stable shed, which now experiences flooding due to the absence of any reinstalled drainage system. The wife deposed that she warned the husband on numerous occasions about the volume of water runoff through the property, but the husband proceeded with earthworks without incorporating sufficient drainage solutions in some areas. As a result, serious water management issues have developed – particularly within the orchard. At the time of the trial, the lower timber retaining walls in that area were failing and at risk of collapse. Full replacement was required according to the wife (the husband did not disagree) which would involve concrete sleepers and steel supports, like those used in the repairs to the carpark retaining wall when it collapsed. The husband accepted that there were also significant drainage issues.

(h) Excavating 10,000 cubic metres and installing two hill dams, and a drainage pit for overflow into the other dam. The wife agreed the husband carried out these works but stated, essentially, poorly. The parties had discussed plans to design and construct gardens below the back dam to manage water overflow in a controlled and aesthetically pleasing manner. The wife deposed that the works that were eventually carried out by the husband as described herein by him, did not reflect what had been discussed or agreed upon. It was further the wife’s evidence that in or about August 2019, the husband began altering the back dam's overflow system by installing a concrete overflow pit with a metal drain that directed water through the roadway and into a newly excavated lower dam. He also commenced building a seven-tiered walled garden around its edges. To contain the dam, he experimented with rock gabion walls and constructed a concrete overflow pit that directed water into a pipe installed beneath the lower garden, ultimately discharging into the neighbour's dam. It was further the wife’s evidence that in or about January 2020, during a sudden two-hour rainfall event delivering 50mm of rain, the dam filled rapidly and rose by approximately two metres, caused significant damage. The water flow washed away most of the newly installed garden edging, along with the rock structures stabilising the overflow chute. The concrete overflow pit was removed and water allowed to flow through to the narrow pipe under the lower garden allowing the natural flow of water through to the neighbour's dam. The site then became unstable, with eroding walls of clay and a serious risk of the whole roadway collapsing and washing into the neighbour's dam. The drain was too narrow to cope with the onslaught of water flowing through it. In or about April 2022, the weather bureau warned of imminent flooding possibly occurring, and the wife arranged, in the absence of the husband, for contractors to put in a proper dam wall along one of the dams. It was the husband’s evidence that he had built on that part of the property, a retarding basin, and not a dam. It was the husband’s complaint that the wife, in carrying out modification works, including a retaining wall whilst he was incarcerated, changed the retarding basin into a dam which caused that dam to fail. In or about October 2022, there was a massive rain event which caused severe flooding throughout the lower garden beds, but the dam wall otherwise contained the water. In about October 2022, the rain event earlier referred to occurred at the G Street property. This caused a huge volume of water to descend on the property in a very short period and caused flooding to parts of the property, resulting in the retarding basin (as referred to by the husband) to overflow down to the gardens area, which was then flooded. The husband had built a permanent water source, and although there was already a wall across it with a tiny drain, the wife was required to urgently put a second wall across the water source to withhold the water, making the retarding basin into a dam. The works performed by the husband in constructing four dams and retaining walls on the G Street property were incomplete or substandard on the evidence of the wife.

(i) Installing two 365,000 litres freshwater tanks which collected water from the roof as conceded by the wife, but her evidence was that the husband’s earlier actions required him to carry out this work. The wife’s evidence was that from 1996 to 2012, the G Street property relied on a self-sustaining natural water system. A rainwater tank provided drinking water, while gravity-fed dam water was used for bathing and household needs. This water was pumped from the back dam to a tank on the hill and then gravity-fed to the house, remaining clear and clean throughout. When the husband commenced earthworks and implemented a drainage system that diverted all the water to the back dam, the water quality deteriorated. The husband attempted to resolve the problem by having filter systems installed but these were unsuccessful. As a result, the new rainwater tanks were urgently installed. The new rainwater tanks now deliver water to the house and shed.

(j) Installing a drainage and pumping system to get water to the house, as conceded by the wife who described these works as the husband upgrading the existing system, with pipes already in situ from the dam to the tank and from the tank to the house.

(k) Installing a sewerage system as conceded by the wife but again, her evidence was that the husband’s earlier actions had caused the need for these works to be carried out. It was the wife’s evidence that the property earlier operated on a low maintenance septic system which required only occasional emptying. When the husband established a orchard along the front roadway and constructed a road around the house, the original septic line was impacted. The husband determined to install a new septic system, designed to irrigate the orchard. Since its installation, on the wife’s evidence, this new system has proven costly and maintenance intensive. It has required three new submerged pumps, regular servicing, and quarterly inspections by TT Pty Ltd, with maintenance costs rising each year.

(l) Installing a one-acre flower garden, comprising five level gardens. The wife conceded these works had been performed by the husband but gave evidence that the works were conducted by the husband without first consulting the wife, and without her prior permission. They were undertaken by the husband when the wife was interstate visiting her sister. Upon her return, she discovered the original house garden had been demolished and replaced with a large rock wall. None of the plants, except two trees, had been saved.

(m) Creating, and planting out three orchards, with raised beds plus upper-level vegetable gardens and raised bed, including taps irrigation and roadways throughout the orchards. The wife conceded these works and thought the orchards “wonderful” but noted that the husband had removed the wife’s original orchard and installed two new orchards. The wife did not request the works be carried out.

(n) Improvements to the house included renovating the bathroom, toilet, laundry, master bedroom, including ensuite with spa, walk in robe, the verandah to the front of the house and bedroom, expanded windows and flooring, with all materials supplied by the husband and any carpenter hire paid by him. The wife conceded these improvements, save the wife claimed that she paid for all the carpenters hired, whilst the husband paid for all the plumbing works around the property.

In about May 2015, the wife’s daughter Ms MM had saved $38,000 from her employment which she gave to her mother, to put the funds into the wife’s bank account to mind for her daughter. With Ms MM’s permission, the wife withdrew bit by bit the entire amount to pay the parties expenses including some of the husband’s legal fees in relation to the various proceedings in which he was involved. These funds were paid back to Ms MM by the husband in 2021.
In mid-2015, the wife became a signatory with the husband to the bank accounts of the husband’s entities and the personal bank accounts of the husband. The wife then commenced to take over the management of the bank accounts and books of the entities except for X Pty Ltd.
In or around January 2016, T Pty Ltd ceased operations.
On 17 June 2016, the husband’s children made an offer to purchase the husband’s shares in X Pty Ltd and the properties owned by B Pty Ltd. The husband rejected that offer.
In September 2016, the wife purchased R Street, City H, Victoria (“the [R Street] Property”). The wife purchased the R Street Property from the Victorian Government for $30,000 and became the sole registered proprietor in September 2016. The wife did not obtain any finance to purchase the R Street Property. The wife funded the purchase through withdrawing her remaining superannuation together with a $10,000 loan from her sister Ms NN. There is a covenant on title restricting the registered proprietor from constructing any habitable dwelling or undertaking any form of residential or commercial use or development on the R Street Property. The property is adjacent to the G Street property and provides enclosure, and prevents the overlooking of, the G Street property.
In late 2016 and in early 2017, the wife received class action settlements totalling $213,358.24. The wife applied these funds toward various joint bills of the husband and wife and toward some of the husband’s debts.
In February 2017, the parties were informed by UU Council that they had breached planning permits in respect of the G Street property. The husband and wife were both charged with carrying out building works at the G Street property without proper permits. They pleaded guilty. No conviction was recorded, but a fine was paid by the husband in the sum of $30,000. The breaches included the following:
(a) a large warehouse and third dwelling/tea room had been developed and was being used as a warehouse, caretakers dwelling, and/or a tea room without planning permissions applicable;

(b) a large dam and “[...]” style detached dwelling had been developed and used as such without planning permissions applicable;

(c) two relocatable site offices had been used for a dwelling or store use without planning permissions applicable;

(d) the land had been used as a depot style transfer station, a store, and for materials recycling and other uses without planning permissions applicable;

(e) earthworks had been conducted on the land, along with the quarrying of rock which had been used to build large retaining walls. Those works occurred without planning permissions applicable; and

(f) council's road reserve was observed to have been developed and occupied without council permission as required.

In August 2017, the husband informed his son, Mr DD, that he would be closing X Pty Ltd. The husband had a meeting with his three children, where he advised them as the managing director that under his son, Mr DD’s, management, the business was “going down and while there was still a business, [he] wanted to sell it”. The husband deposed that his son Mr CC told him they would take the husband to Court to stop him from selling the business, and that his daughter told him “All hell would break loose” if the husband tried to sell the business. The meeting ended with no resolution.
In October 2017, the husband, having commenced a subdivision of 3 J Street on the J Street property, into 4 J Street and 4 L Street, required a further $100,000 to finalise the sub-division.
In November 2017, the wife’s sister, Ms NN, deposited $100,000 in the husband’s bank account (the husband was unable to obtain funds from the major banks) to enable him to complete the subdivision. She also provided a further $19,000 in payment of further expenses relating to the subdivision. The monies were advanced by way of loan and repaid by the husband in 2021.
In November 2017, the police attended the G Street property and took the husband to the Suburb VV police station where he was told that Ms EE, his daughter, had made criminal allegations against the husband of indecent assault for an incident that allegedly occurred in 1984.
In 2017, the wife ceased working as a healthcare professional. Her administrative workload as carried out on behalf of the husband had increased and, because of the husband’s various pieces of litigation, would increase further.
In 2017, the husband’s former wife Ms Y applied to the then Family Court (now the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia (Division 1)) to re-open property settlement proceedings reached between she and the husband as set out in consent orders of the Court. Ms Y was unsuccessful and transferred a property owned by her, known as Remote Location N, to the husband to meet her costs obligations to him. The husband became the sole registered proprietor of Remote Location N in August 2020. The husband’s costs of this litigation were, however, $800,000, representing an overall not insignificant loss to the husband.
In early 2018, Mr DD commenced proceedings in the Supreme Court of Victoria SCI [...] seeking, amongst other orders, injunctions against the husband and X Pty Ltd and B Pty Ltd, to remove the husband as director and appointor of trusts, and for B Pty Ltd to be removed as trustee of K Trust and Guttenberg Trust.
In late 2018, the husband applied to the Supreme Court of Victoria for a receiver to be appointed to X Pty Ltd (SCI [...]).
In May 2019, 5 L Street as subdivided by the husband with respect to the L Street property was sold by the husband for a total purchase price, including GST, of $3,600,000. The net proceeds of sale were applied by the husband to the payment of his and his entities’ legal fees due to BB Lawyers.
In late 2019, Mr DD and the husband and their entities entered a Deed of Settlement in the Supreme Court proceedings whereby it was agreed that, amongst other things:
(a) the husband would resign as a director of X Pty Ltd, transfer all his shares in X Pty Ltd to Mr DD and resign as the appointor of the Guttenberg Trust; and

(b) B Pty Ltd would enter into a commercial lease with X Pty Ltd.

Pursuant to the settlement, the husband ceased to be a director and secretary of X Pty Ltd. The husband’s shares in X Pty Ltd were transferred to Mr DD in late 2019.
On 18 November 2019 and 22 November 2019, B Pty Ltd issued Notices of Breach to X Pty Ltd, for failure by X Pty Ltd to pay rent.
On 8 December 2019, the husband changed the locks at the premises being occupied by X Pty Ltd.
In late 2019, the husband and/or his entities, commenced County Court of Victoria proceedings against X Pty Ltd for unpaid present entitlements. The matter proceeded to trial, and, in October 2022, judgment was entered by Judge [...] in favour of X Pty Ltd against the husband’s entities, together with costs awarded in favour of X Pty Ltd.
In late 2019, X Pty Ltd commenced proceedings in the Supreme Court of Victoria SCI [...] against B Pty Ltd and the husband to set aside the Notices of Breach and to enforce the commercial lease component of the 6 September 2019 Deed of Settlement.
On 12 January 2021, a liquidator was appointed to T Pty Ltd.
Between 2021 and 2023, the husband spent an amount of more than $200,000 on his machinery. The wife submitted the costs spent by the husband were not proportionate to the total value of the plant and equipment at that time. That expenditure is probably reflected in the current valuation of the plant and equipment, but that same value cannot then be used to assess the husband’s initial contribution of plant and equipment at $571,000, and there must be some discretionary approach to that sum as claimed.
In late 2021, the husband was sentenced to a jail term in relation to the indecent assault of his daughter. He was released on parole after several months.
On 12 November 2021, the husband gave the wife power of attorney for the operations of D Pty Ltd, B Pty Ltd, and C Pty Ltd, and a personal enduring power of attorney.
On 15 November 2021, the wife removed $1,300,000 from the D Pty Ltd WW Bank and placed such monies into her account to protect the money from the husband’s children. The wife paid, into her superannuation fund, $100,000 of these funds. She retained these funds and used them in the years ahead to support herself and pay for household and other expenses of the parties.
On 19 November 2021, the wife transferred the remaining $1,200,000 from her account to her Retirement account.
In early 2022, the wife applied $100,000 of the funds withdrawn by her to urgent rectification works needing to be carried out to the G Street property. The application of these funds by the wife was, I find, necessary to preserve the assets of the parties. That expenditure occurred prior to the July 2025 valuation of the property. The balance was applied to daily expenses and joint bills of the parties, and the husband’s entities, over time including during the husband’s incarceration.
In February 2022, the Suburb F Property was first marketed for sale. The husband had informed the wife that he wanted to sell the Suburb F Property. When the husband was in jail, the wife organised for the Suburb F Property to be listed for sale, including liaising with selling agents and solicitors.
In mid-2022, the husband was released from incarceration.
In August 2022, the husband resigned as director of D Pty Ltd, and the wife was appointed as sole director. The husband retained all 1000 shares.
In late 2022, the Honourable Justice [...] in the Supreme Court of Victoria made orders for B Pty Ltd to enter a lease with X Pty Ltd in respect of a part of the J Street property and commencing September 2019. The lease agreement provided for rental of $24,761.19 each month ($297,134.28 per annum) plus outgoings as asserted by the wife, less GST. Those monies were and continue to be received by the husband.
The husband and his son, at the trial of these proceedings, were again in conflict with no agreement being reached as to the increase in rent as demanded by the husband on a rent review, with this dispute first commencing in the middle of 2024. In the interim, the rental received by the husband has remained the same. The husband anticipated that the Supreme Court of Victoria would need to appoint a valuer to settle the dispute.
In late 2023, X Pty Ltd was awarded judgment of $269,735.06 in its favour in relation to the 2019 Supreme Court proceedings by Justice [...], with the question of costs to still be determined.
On 23 August 2023, the first loan from GG Limited was refinanced. As part of the refinance, $2,845,292.31, representing a part of the loan funds, were dispersed to C Pty Ltd by GG Limited. It is from these funds that the wife and husband withdrew further monies as referred to below.
On 13 September 2023, the parties transferred $610,000 from the C Pty Ltd WW Bank account into a separate bank account in the name of C Pty Ltd, for the sole purpose of making interest payments to GG Limited ($54,903.25 per month for 11 months).
On 18 October 2023, the parties separated but remained living under the same roof.
On 18 October 2023, the wife made withdrawals totalling $1,750,000 from the WW Bank Account of C Pty Ltd. The wife did so to provide financial security for herself and to meet the payment expenses of the husband’s entities and the parties’ usual expenses; to pay for further rectification works to the G Street property; and to pay any impending legal costs incurred by her.
In October 2023, the husband removed the wife as director and secretary of D Pty Ltd. The husband became the sole director and secretary and otherwise at around this time, the husband revoked all corporate and personal powers that he had previously given to the wife.
In late 2023, costs were awarded in favour of X Pty Ltd. An order was made in mid-2025 by a Registrar in the Supreme Court of Victoria Proceeding SCI [...] that the taxable costs be fixed at $503,000.
In late 2023, the husband issued an urgent application to the Court for the return of the funds withdrawn by the wife on 18 October 2023.
In late 2023, the Court made orders which provided for the sale of the Suburb F Property. The following orders were also made in respect of the monies withdrawn by the wife from the WW Bank account of C Pty Ltd in October 2023 of $1,750,00, it being accepted by the husband that some of those funds were applied to the husband’s entities and/or for the husband’s benefit:
...
That from the balance of moneys retained by the Respondent, the sum of $100,000 be by way of part property settlement.
That the Respondent immediately return to the Applicant, the remainder of the funds that she removed from the [WW Bank] [Account No...] on 18 October 2023 in the amount of approximately $1,050,000 to the [WW Bank] [Account No...] or such other account as nominated by the Applicant in writing.
In December 2023, the wife commenced to undertake some further rectification works to the G Street property. The works undertaken by her since December 2023 include:
(a) rectification of two dams on the south hill gullies which were dug out by the husband: compacting soil on front bank and re-seeding surrounding area and installing swales along the contours of the two gullies (including re-seeding) to prevent further erosion;

(b) rectification of the car park installed by the husband. The redgum sleeper retaining wall failed resulting in water pouring down the hill and out between the sleepers, due to lack of adequate drainage at the time of installation. The redgum sleepers were replaced with concrete sleepers;

(c) repair of gutters along the front roadway which had washed out;

(d) repair of the front gate and installation of a new electric security system;

(e) the installation of a plumbing sanitiser due to the presence of E. Coli in the water tanks; and

(f) minor plumbing works around the house.

On 6 December 2023, the wife transferred to C Pty Ltd bank account the sum of $1,222,000. The wife retained $34,000 as paid to her lawyer and $25,000 as expended by her for her living and other needs. This was reasonable in the circumstances given the parties disparity in income receipt and available assets.
In March/April 2024, the wife undertook further non-urgent rectification works to the G Street property. She applied some of the funds obtained by her from the C Pty Ltd WW Bank account as ordered to remain with her.
In June 2024, the husband became the registered proprietor of the Town Q property. The purchase price of that was $340,000 with the funds being derived from the C Pty Ltd WW Bank Account. The house was not habitable, and the husband spent $60,000 to make it habitable, with a further $100,000 to be applied in renovating the property as calculated by the husband.
On 14 July 2024, the husband moved out from the G Street property, to stay at XX Hotel, until the Town Q property he had purchased was habitable.
Upon the husband’s departure from the G Street property, the husband left his equipment in storage on the wife’s property, despite her wish, ongoing, for him to remove such property. The husband’s evidence in cross-examination, was that it was “necessary” for him to put his equipment on the wife’s land at the time he did so, as 80 per cent of such equipment was taken to her property to be used on her property. When put to the husband that such equipment was no longer used on the wife’s property, the husband’s reply was “she told me to leave”. The husband’s further evidence was at the time of his moving his equipment to the wife’s property, it was not possible for him to find an alternative site, and that doing so would have cost a lot of money.
In August 2024, the husband was unable to refinance the Suburb F Property and defaulted on the $54,903 monthly repayments.
On 20 August 2024, orders were made by consent for the husband to do all things reasonably required to continue the sale process of the Suburb F Property and for the proceeds of sale to be applied, relevantly, as follows:
(a) to pay the costs and commissions of the sale;

(b) to discharge any registered encumbrance;
(c) to pay the defacto wife (“the wife”) the sum of $250,000 by way of part property settlement as follows:
(i) $50,000 on exchange of contract;

(ii) $200,000 on settlement.
...
At the time of trial, the part property settlement of $250,000 had not been paid to the wife.
In September 2024, the husband drove to the G Street property. The gates were closed. The husband drove through the gates, leaving them damaged on the ground. Prior to this incident, the husband had been staying at XX Hotel and had inadvertently failed to inform the police of his change of address, which he was required to do following his release from incarceration. The owners of the hotel told the husband he could no longer stay there. He had then stayed for a few nights at YY Hotel, but they no longer had available accommodation thereafter. Having driven through the gates to the wife’s property, the husband drove up to the house and entered it before going to bed there. The wife was not on the property. The wife subsequently allowed the husband to stay at the G Street property, as she was away for a few nights. The husband paid the sum of $2,000 to the wife as compensation for property damage. The police charged the husband for criminal property damage and failure to inform them of his address.
In September 2024, the husband returned to the G Street property. The wife saw him taking tablets through his car window. The husband drove off into the bush, and the wife called emergency services and organised for both the Police and ambulance to attend. The Police and ambulance arrived shortly after and located the husband in the bush. The Police broke the husband’s car window. The ambulance took him to ZZ Hospital which then transferred him to AB Mental Health Services. He was admitted for three days as he had attempted suicide by overdose.
In October 2024, the police obtained a 12-month intervention order against the husband with the wife as the aggrieved person in need of protection, in the Town AC Magistrates Court. The husband consented to the order without admission.
In December 2024, T Pty was deregistered.
In January 2025, GG Limited took possession of the Suburb F Property because of C Pty Ltd being in default of the loan to GG Limited. On the husband’s evidence, he had earlier spent approximately $500,000 (it was submitted on his behalf that he had expended costs of $120,000) on preparing the property for sale, with those monies derived from the C Pty Ltd WW Bank account. No probative evidence was before the Court to establish the quantum spent by the husband. It was the husband’s evidence that after he defaulted on the loan, GG Limited applied a default interest rate such that the monthly repayments on the loan became $77,540.
In early 2025, the Suburb F Property was sold by mortgagee auction for the sum of $8,400,000 with settlement due 12 months from the date of sale. The estimated amount required at settlement to discharge the mortgage was $7,321,532.55. The husband’s evidence is that the equity remaining will be taken up in the payment of Capital Gains Tax; 2026 land tax and body corporate fees for the J Street and L Street properties; and legal costs as owed by the husband. The balance remaining is anticipated to be approximately $1,078,468.
In mid-2025, a criminal hearing took place regarding the charges against the husband of property damage and failure to inform the police of his address. The husband received a 12-month good behaviour bond and had to donate to the Country Fire Authority (CFA).
At trial, the husband no longer had any interest in X Pty Ltd or the Guttenberg Trust. The husband is no longer a director, shareholder, appointor, beneficiary and/or other office holder of these two entities. Whilst he had the interests that he did at the commencement of cohabitation, he lost them and spent exorbitant amounts in litigation that provided no financial benefit to the parties, rather consistent debt.

LEGAL PRINCIPLES

Section 90SM(3) of the Act provides:
(3) The court shall not make an order under this section unless it is satisfied that, in all the circumstances, it is just and equitable to make the order.
It is necessary to first identify the existing legal and equitable property interests of the parties. It must not be assumed the parties’ rights to or interests in property are or should be different from those that then exist, or that a party has the right to have the parties’ property divided by reference to the statutory considerations (see Stanford v Stanford [2012] FamCAFC 1; (2012) 247 CLR 108 at [37]– [40] and [50]).
Although in Stanford v Stanford [2012] FamCAFC 1; (2012) 247 CLR 108 the High Court was dealing with an application between spouses for property settlement pursuant to Pt VIII of the Act, the principles apply equally to applications between de facto partners pursuant to Pt VIIIAB of the Act.
If and once determined it is just and equitable for the identified property interests of the parties to be altered, the process of evaluating the proper orders to make is dictated by the factors enumerated within s 90SM(4) of the Act. The Court must necessarily identify and assess the parties’ contributions within the meaning of ss 90SM(4)(a)–(c) and then take account of the relevant matters referred to in ss 90SM(4)(d)–(g) and 90SF(3) of the Act.
Section 90SM(4) of the Act provides:
(4) In considering what order (if any) should be made under this section in property settlement proceedings, the court must take into account:
(a) the financial contribution made directly or indirectly by or on behalf of a party to the de facto relationship, or a child of the de facto relationship:
(i) to the acquisition, conservation or improvement of any of the property of the parties to the de facto relationship or either of them; or
(ii) otherwise in relation to any of that last - mentioned property;
whether or not that last - mentioned property has, since the making of the contribution, ceased to be the property of the parties to the de facto relationship or either of them; and
(b) the contribution (other than a financial contribution) made directly or indirectly by or on behalf of a party to the de facto relationship, or a child of the de facto relationship:
(i) to the acquisition, conservation or improvement of any of the property of the parties to the de facto relationship or either of them; or
(ii) otherwise in relation to any of that last - mentioned property;
whether or not that last - mentioned property has, since the making of the contribution, ceased to be the property of the parties to the de facto relationship or either of them; and
(c) the contribution made by a party to the de facto relationship to the welfare of the family constituted by the parties to the de facto relationship and any children of the de facto relationship, including any contribution made in the capacity of homemaker or parent; and

(d) the effect of any proposed order upon the earning capacity of either party to the de facto relationship; and

(e) the matters referred to in subsection 90SF(3) so far as they are relevant; and

(f) any other order made under this Act affecting a party to the de facto relationship or a child of the de facto relationship; and

(g) any child support under the Child Support (Assessment) Act 1989 that a party to the de facto relationship has provided, is to provide, or might be liable to provide in the future, for a child of the de facto relationship.

Section 90SF(3) of the Act provides, relevantly:
(3) The matters to be so taken into account are:
(a) the age and state of health of each of the parties to the de facto relationship (the subject de facto relationship); and

(b) the income, property and financial resources of each of the parties and the physical and mental capacity of each of them for appropriate gainful employment; and

(c) whether either party has the care or control of a child of the de facto relationship who has not attained the age of 18 years; and

(d) commitments of each of the parties that are necessary to enable the party to support:

(i) himself or herself; and
(ii) a child or another person that the party has a duty to maintain; and
(e) the responsibilities of either party to support any other person; and
(f) subject to subsection (4), the eligibility of either party for a pension, allowance or benefit under:
(i) any law of the Commonwealth, of a State or Territory or of another country; or

(ii) any superannuation fund or scheme, whether the fund or scheme was established, or operates, within or outside Australia;

and the rate of any such pension, allowance or benefit being paid to either party; and
(g) a standard of living that in all the circumstances is reasonable;

...
(q) any child support under the Child Support (Assessment) Act 1989 that a party to the subject de facto relationship has provided, is to provide, or might be liable to provide in the future, for a child of the subject de facto relationship; and

(r) any fact or circumstance which, in the opinion of the court, the justice of the case requires to be taken into account;

...
It is permissible for the factors prescribed by s 90SM(4) (the counterpart to s 79(4)) to inform the inquiry under s 90SM(3) (the counterpart to s 79(2)) of the Act about the justice and equity of making property settlement orders (see Bevan & Bevan [2013] FamCAFC 116; (2013) FLC 93-545 at [83]–[89], [163], [169] and [171]–[172]).
In undertaking the task of considering the totality of the parties’ contributions in a holistic manner, it is inappropriate for a trial judge to adopt an ‘accounting’ or ‘scoring’ approach to each separate contribution. As explained by the Full Court in Blandford & Esmore [2022] FedCFamC1A 67 at [14], adopting such an approach is flawed because it “would not only require detailed actuarial calculations with respect to financial contributions (which would rarely be possible on the evidence generally available in property settlement cases), but it would still leave the significant problem of how to convert the qualitative factors in s 90SM(4)(b) and s 90SM(4)(c) of the [Act]”.
Section 90SS of the Act grants specific powers to a Court to make a range of different orders to adjust property interests between the parties.

EVIDENCE

The husband

The husband was generally a reliable witness and certainly he tried to be responsive to questions asked of him in cross-examination. He made concessions about his poor memory, saying that the depression from which he suffered had been “bad” since 2007, and he had, consequently, some memory lapses. The husband gave evasive evidence at times, and he exaggerated his contributions in part. His evidence did not assist the Court in attempting to establish what equity he had in his real properties at the commencement of cohabitation, whether owned personally or through his entities.

The wife

The wife was a reliable witness, responsive and honest, and I accept her evidence. Where it differed from the husband’s I preferred that of the wife except if indicated otherwise.

Ms W

Ms W, the accountant of the husband, was requested by the husband to provide an estimate of the capital gains tax arising from the sale of the property at E Street, Suburb F. The capital gain was valued by her at $172,558.94 and would be taxed at the company tax rate of 30 per cent. It was her expert opinion, therefore, that provision for the taxable amount due should be approximately $51,767.70.

Mr Steven Kincaid

Mr Kincaid was a Certified Practising Valuer, employed with FF Pty Ltd. He provided a valuation report on the equipment at the G Street property. His expert opinion was that the total Fair Market Value of the assets on an "As is - Where is" basis, excluding GST, was $571,600. The husband did not challenge that evidence but gave evidence that the value had since been reduced by approximately $20,000 because:
(a) he provided a prime mover (as valued by Mr Kincaid at $12,000) owned by him, to a friend to drive. The prime mover was written off by the friend and was not insured. The husband’s further evidence was that it may, but not necessarily probably, be able to be sold for scrap metal or spare parts and may achieve a sale price of $800-$1000 or $2000; and

(b) the wife damaged Motor Vehicle 2 which has made it worthless.

The Court accepts that the valuation of Mr Kincaid should be reduced by the $20,000 as claimed by the husband.

