CONTRIBUTIONS

In Gadhavi & Gadhavi [2023] FedCFamC1A 117, the Full Court said at [31] – [33]:
...In Pierce v Pierce [1998] FamCA 74; (1999) FLC 92-844 (“Pierce”), the Full Court stated at [28]:
...It is necessary to weigh the initial contributions by a party with all other relevant contributions of both the husband and the wife. In considering the weight to be attached to the initial contribution, in this case of the husband, regard must be had to the use made by the parties of that contribution.

...
To similar effect, in Cabbell & Cabbell [2009] FamCAFC 205, the Full Court stated at [54] that in considering the parties’ contributions, it is necessary to trace the use of those assets and consider the foundation that they laid for the subsequent accumulation of wealth by the parties.

That is, in evaluating the parties’ contributions, it was necessary for the primary judge to have regard to the context of the husband’s initial contribution and specifically, to the opportunity that initial contribution created and the impact of that initial contribution on the subsequent wealth of the parties as at the date of the hearing.
The wife’s position was that the parties have made equal contributions (both financial and non-financial) to the acquisition, conservation and/or improvement of the property of the parties, over a relationship which lasted more than 11 years. She asserted acknowledgement of the initial contributions of the husband in terms of her claim to a less than equal adjustment, being 45 per cent.
The husband submitted that most contributions, particularly financial, came from the husband, and that the bulk of the asset pool as it currently exists is a result of what the husband contributed to the parties’ net asset pool. The husband claimed to have made initial contributions of at least $8,181,000, calculated in part by application of the retrospective values of each the properties owned by him and/or his entities.

Commencement of cohabitation

At the commencement of cohabitation, being January 2012, the husband and/or his entities owned the following real properties and equipment, excluding that as described in [26] and [27] above (as agreed by the husband):
(a) J Street, Suburb M, with a retrospective value of $3,600,000;

(b) E Street, Suburb F with a retrospective value of $3,300,000;

(c) 1 L Street with a retrospective value of $610,000;

(d) 2 L Street with no retrospective value, a mortgage in unknown sum from 2009 to sale, and a sale price in January 2021 of $920,000; and

(e) the plant and machinery for D Pty Ltd, presently valued at $571,000 but in relation to which a prime mover and car with a combined value of $20,000 approximately no longer exist (leaving plant and machinery at $551,000); and observing that the husband had expended some significant monies ($200,000) between 2021 and 2023 as described above.

The husband also had his interest in the various entities as described in the relevant facts, and in the assets and liabilities of the parties. The husband also had his ownership of the QQ Street property in which he had resided which, during cohabitation, he proceeded to subdivide.
The husband relied on the retrospective valuations in evidence to establish his significant contributions. He did not, however, disclose the extent of his liabilities as attached to the real property as owned by the husband and/or his entities, being the mortgage encumbrances over those properties as owned by him and/or his entities. For instance, the husband’s undisclosed mortgage loan to the Commonwealth Bank of Australia over 2 L Street Suburb M; the undisclosed mortgage loan to Westpac bank over the Suburb F Property, purchased for $1.8 million, and which commenced in November 2007 and was not discharged until January 2020; and the J Street property mortgage, which the wife calculated on purchase to be $1.3 million (see [28] above). A retrospective net value of $2.3 million rather than the $3.6 million was established. The husband also made no reference to any mortgage with respect to the QQ Street property, although the cost of subdivision was $1.5 million on his evidence, with the initial cost of purchase and means of purchase being undisclosed.
At the commencement of cohabitation, the wife owned the G Street property, with a retrospective value of $500,000. She had a very small mortgage, resulting in a net equity of $467,078.75. The wife paid out this mortgage in the following year from her pre-existing superannuation entitlements which she could then access. The wife also had Motor Vehicle 1, some savings, modest farm equipment and at least $50,000 superannuation (and possibly $100,000). On the evidence, I could make no exact finding.
The wife’s initial contributions appeared to be only five per cent of the parties’ initial contributions, but the husband’s lack of disclosure made that assessment probably inaccurate. It is unlikely, however, that the wife’s initial contributions exceeded eight per cent.

During cohabitation

During cohabitation, the wife applied her compensation settlement payments of $213,358.24 toward the parties’ expenses and the parties’ debts.
During cohabitation, the wife purchased, without mortgage, the R Street Property, using her superannuation and a loan from her sister, which probably remains unpaid.
During cohabitation, the wife’s sister and the wife’s daughter provided interest-free loans to the husband, which he repaid some years later.
During the relationship, the husband acquired his interest in Remote Location N in Region O which had an agreed retrospective value of $100,000 as at 1 January 2012 and, at trial, a value of $400,000, as agreed between the parties. However, the husband expended $800,000 in legal costs making this a loss outcome.
During the parties’ cohabitation, the husband generated income to pay for the parties’ living expenses solely from 2017, and to pay for those debts incurred as part of the operation of his business, and to pay for his acquisition of real property and subdivision expenses, although he was always paying mortgage repayments in respect of various properties, and paying legal costs in large sums, from which the wife benefitted not at all, and which were incurred by the husband and/or his entities solely. The husband provided no evidence as to the costs incurred by him in respect of his criminal trial, but they would probably have been substantial.
The wife’s income helped to support the household until 2017. It was not insignificant, albeit the husband tried to make it so, given the parties very modest living expenses. The wife was the primary homemaker. The wife’s unencumbered home provided accommodation for the parties, and the wife’s land became a free repository for the husband to store his extensive plant and equipment and other materials. The cost to the husband and/or his entities in leasing a suitable property to store his plant and equipment was considerable. The husband wished to avoid that. The extent of the husband’s storage arrangement is reflected in part in the UU Council’s list of complaints as they appear elsewhere in these reasons.
The wife assisted the husband and his companies through at least eight pieces of litigation, with the husband being unable to manage the ongoing litigation by himself.
The wife also managed the bank accounts and the books for the husband’s corporate entities and was added as a signatory to the husband’s personal and entities’ bank accounts.
The wife assisted the husband in reviving his business through T Pty Ltd which lasted for a period of approximately 14 months.
The wife also provided to the husband considerable emotional and physical support, as well as caring for him by ensuring his taking of necessary medication. The husband also provided emotional and physical support to the wife.
The husband performed extensive works on the wife’s G Street property. The works the husband performed on the G Street property were not at the request of the wife – the property had sufficient infrastructure prior to the works, including roadways, tracks, shedding to accommodate machinery, float and trailers, and an adequate hay shed for stockfeed. Rather, they were carried out, on the one hand, because the husband thought they would enhance the property, and he was genuinely very interested in creating gardens and orchards, having goats and other animals and, on the other, because he wanted to provide storage for his plant and equipment, and supply accommodation for the workers as employed by him. The wife very much appreciated the gazebo placed on a pillar in the middle of the house dam; the gardens; the orchards; and the house dam itself, with the wife describing them in her evidence as “wonderful”. Other works were problematic. Overall, they increased the value of the wife’s property by $350,000, but there is probative evidence, as provided by the wife, which I accept, that significant rectification work has needed to be done, and will continue to need to be done. The costs are indeterminate in that there was no expert evidence for the Court to draw any conclusions about that, but there was the husband’s assessment, against his own interests, that the cost would be approximately $500,000.
During their cohabitation, the parties shared the household expenses until 2017. Whilst they still had separate bank accounts at commencement of their cohabitation, they pooled some of their resources and expenses.
During the latter part of the cohabitation, the wife commenced to transfer to her accounts regular amounts of $10,000 from the C Pty Ltd Bank Account, which held loan monies. Such transfers as were made during the parties’ relationship were utilised for their necessary expenses which included payment of the husband’s and/or his entities’ invoices.
The wife supported the husband through all the litigation that he and/or his entities were a party to. The husband conceded that the wife helped him in his litigation and that in the years 2019 to 2021, she spent a lot of time engaged in his litigations. She also assisted him in his criminal proceedings, providing both effective and practical administrative support, together with moral support, the latter as described by the husband.
The parties contributions throughout this period favoured the wife.

Post-separation

Rectification works are needed on the G Street property. That is not in dispute. When asked about them in cross-examination, the husband stated that to fix works that needed fixing, he would finish everything he had started. The husband stated that he would fix the drains, the concerning dam and the dam wall, the wall he said being washed away from what he claimed was a surge of water. He would make repairs to the roads, and perform maintenance works on retaining wall. He would place a drain down the side of the driveway and would concrete the problematic drain. He would install a bitumen road, among other things. It was the husband’s evidence that he would take about two months of working six or seven days a week at a cost of $500,000 to perform what rectification works the wife had engaged a contractor to perform, and to replace some of the works that he had undertaken.
Following separation under the one roof, the wife paid the household bills from her own funds, and the husband did not contribute to any household expenses save he would occasionally purchase groceries.
The husband acquired the Town Q property with a value of $400,000, using the GG Limited loan monies in the C Pty Ltd WW Bank account.
The husband obtained valuations in the first instance throughout the litigation. The wife had earlier agreed that she should pay to the husband the sum of $27,297.50, being one half of such costs. However, the litigation process has been long, and the wife has been without income, having an inability to obtain a pension because of the husband’s assets. The husband has a significant income stream and although needed to meet his commitments, he has considerable assets at his disposal including plant and equipment no longer used by him. It is appropriate, just and equitable in the context of the factual circumstances here, that the husband pay solely the costs of the valuations and mediation without reimbursement as to one-half by the wife, and any orders to the contrary shall be discharged.
The works conducted by the husband to the G Street property have left the property in a mess and in disarray. The wife has already undertaken some urgent rectification works, listed elsewhere in this judgment. It was the wife’s evidence that significant (unspecified) costs will be required to rectify and restore the damage caused due to the earthworks carried out by the husband, and his flattening of the land.
The wife has been left with the plant and equipment of the husband, being stored on her property. Consequently, her property, in part, is a heavy industrial storage site, and that sight intrudes upon the farming landscape. The wife has had to deal with that to the present time. While the husband has been restrained from entering upon the property or within 200 metres of the property pursuant to the IVO, and in effect from removing this equipment, the husband is aware, and has been for some time, that the wife wishes for him to plan for the removal of the equipment. While the wife’s property has been a storage site, the husband has saved considerable rental monies that would otherwise be needed to be expended by him. The husband suggested that such rental could be approximately $1,000 a week.
It was the husband’s evidence that there would be difficulty in him finding an alternate site. His evidence was that he would need a further period of 6 to 18 months to find another heavy industrial site. In the interim, his proposal was that he would simply leave the equipment, rent-free, where it is. That is not a just and equitable outcome. The husband has been aware of the wife’s wish for the equipment to be sold or removed by an agent of the husband since separation. The husband has always been able to retain ownership of these assets or to retain the net proceeds of sale. That shall now change if the wife is required to conduct a sale on her property because of the husband’s refusal to comply with an order for removal of the plant and equipment in a timely way. I shall propose a payment to the wife of 20% of the net proceeds as just recompense and as a means of having the husband act before it becomes necessary for the wife to take on this arduous and unwanted task.
The wife has also had to deal with the husband’s behaviours, which included her need to obtain an IVO against him.
The wife’s contributions in this period have exceeded those of the husband.

Section 90SF(3) factors

The wife was 77 years of age at the time of trial. The wife suffers from moderately severe osteoarthritis in both of her hands. She takes medication for high cholesterol and has undergone a knee replacement in 2022. She suffers from chronic sleep apnoea which has caused minor left ventricular failure. The wife is unable to return to paid employment.
The husband was 78 years of age at the time of trial. He suffers from bipolar disorder and depression. He is not working and probably unable to work.
The wife has been retired since 2017, before which she worked as a healthcare professional. The wife receives currently no income either in paid employment or pension from Centrelink or her superannuation fund. Following her retirement, she was reliant upon the husband for the parties’ general living expenses until separation of the parties. The wife has been unable to apply for a pension due to the assets of the husband. It is not possible for the wife to derive an income from the orchards and vegetable gardens as built by husband. The G Street property is a hobby farm and not a commercial venture. Wild animals (birds, kangaroos, rabbits, wild ducks, deer and wombats) have eaten plants in the garden, making the trees and vegetable gardens unviable in any capacity without being netted and closed off to wildlife. The produce from the trees is not enough in any event to supply a commercial venture. The produce the parties did get from the trees and gardens was generally shared with friends and family, with any excess donated to a local charity. The wife’s expenses are $1,200 per week.
The wife is seeking spousal maintenance payments of $750 each week until receipt of the payment from the husband. The husband earns approximately $7,564 (including GST) from his interests in the entities per week. The husband has average weekly expenses and liabilities at approximately $17,842. This leaves a significant shortfall of just over $10,000 a week. He is not eligible for a pension and he has no superannuation. The husband submitted that he does not have financial capacity to pay spousal maintenance to the wife.
I do not propose to make a spousal maintenance payment in the circumstances of the case. The wife will be excused from the need to pay to the husband the $27,000 amount as referred to above and she has had the use of the $100,000 earlier expressed part-payment of property. The husband has debts beyond his income to meet, is living in accommodation that needs improvement, and is not to a reasonable standard at the present time and is not working and aged. I observe the wife’s accommodation is comfortable and reasonable. The parties wide ranging needs and ability to provide for them at the present time, without a sale of further assets by the husband, is equal. I have considered the differential in the parties’ respective financial positions because of the outcome of these proceedings and find no need for any further adjustment by way of ongoing spousal maintenance currently. If the circumstances change, the wife will be able to further agitate this claim.
The three site offices presently on the wife’s property, with a value in the plant and equipment valuation of $4,000, shall remain the property of the wife. The justice and equity of the case require this outcome as these structures have been on the wife’s property for many years, can be used by the wife, and add value to her property. They now form part of the G Street property and are fully connected to electricity and stormwater. Planning and building approvals were obtained for these site offices. The husband has not chosen to remove them. It would be inequitable for the wife to now be required to pay the husband to retain those assets.

CONCLUSION

The question as to what became of the initial contributions of the husband is answered as follows:
(a) The J Street property, purchased in October 2001, with a likely mortgage or mortgages of $1.3 million and thus having a net value of $2.3 million, had increased from a retrospective valuation of $3.6 million to $4.9 million. That latter figure will have mortgages attached, though in what quantum was not placed before the Court by the husband. Throughout the course of cohabitation, the husband carried out subdivisions on this property. One of those remains as 1 L Street Suburb M, Victoria. Otherwise, the husband received sale proceeds of more than $3 million in respect of one of the subdivisions, which was totally expended in the payment of his and his businesses’ costs to BB Lawyers.

(b) 1 L Street Suburb M, Victoria, with a retrospective value of $610,000, has increased in value to $920,000 and remains an asset of the husband’s entities. That is, it has increased in value by $310,000 and it is probable that, throughout cohabitation, a mortgage was paid out of income in respect of this property.

(c) 2 L Street, Suburb M was sold in January 2021 and the net proceeds of the sale of $920,000 were applied in their totality to further legal costs of the husband and/or his entities. Throughout the cohabitation period of nine years before sale a mortgage was paid in respect of this property, most probably out of income as received by the husband and his entities. That asset no longer exists.

(d) The plant and equipment as held by the husband was transferred to the property of the wife and used by the husband to carry out the various works as done by him. These works added value to the wife’s property in the value of $350,000 but also caused damage, causing rectification works in unknown sum. The husband also applied $200,000 at least toward the maintaining of this plant and equipment and not long before the current valuation was obtained of now $551,000.

(e) The Suburb F Property had a retrospective value of $3.3 million. It had been purchased by the husband in November 2007 for $1.8 million with mortgage encumbrances which were discharged in January 2020. During eight years of cohabitation, mortgage instalments in respect of this property were paid. In October 2021, the husband refinanced with GG Limited and the property has since been sold, with the husband estimating the net sale proceeds that he might receive after payment of his liabilities to be approximately $880,000–$1 million.

(f) The QQ Street property, with no retrospective valuation as obtained by the husband, and no details as to its purchase price nor mortgage encumbrances at the time of acquisition, before 2012, was sold during the parties’ cohabitation and, after a subdivision, achieved a sale price of $6,372,000. In 2014, the husband received the net proceeds of approximately $1,211,000. I observe that mortgage instalments were paid by the husband from 2012 to 2014. The husband applied those net proceeds to company expenses and a claimed payout of all his then existing mortgages, which was clearly not accurate. The mortgages encumbering the QQ Street property were paid out.

I am satisfied that in all the circumstances of this case it is appropriate, just and equitable to make orders altering the parties’ property interests.
The wife has assets of $1,424,263, a little more than 16 per cent of the net asset pool of the parties of $8,615,855. In the exercise of my broad discretion, I have determined on the facts of this case and the law applicable that the significant differential in the parties’ initial contributions, and the outcome of the tracing of the use and any retention of those assets, in the context of the parties’ lifestyle and now accumulated wealth, coupled with the totality of contributions as made by the parties over the course of their cohabitation, and post, and considering also the matters relevant in section 90SF(3) of the Act, that there be an adjustment of the parties net assets as to 33 per cent to the wife ($2,843,232.15) and 67 per cent to the husband ($5,772,622.85) (that is, a differential of $2,929,390.70) requiring a cash payment of $1,418,969.15 from the husband to the wife. The wife has, however, had the benefit of an advance of $350,000, pursuant to existing orders of the Court made 20 August 2024 ($250,000) and 4 December 2023 ($100,000). The advance of $100,000 was, however, required by the wife to be applied to urgent and other rectification works in respect of the works carried out by the husband on the G Street property. It is, therefore, not just and equitable, nor appropriate, to find that such advance should be regarded as a capital payment which must now be deducted out of the wife’s ultimate adjustment. Accordingly, such sums as shall be deducted from the wife’s 33 per cent adjustment, in terms of the earlier orders made, are limited to the $250,000 due to her from the sale of the Suburb F Property, as ordered by the Court. After deduction of this sum (if received by the wife), the payment would be $1,168,969.15. If such monies have not been paid to the wife, then such monies shall not be deducted.
The works required to be conducted by the wife to rectify the damage caused by the husband to the G Street property, are expected to be of significant cost but there was no expert evidence to support a finding by the Court as to a precise cost. The wife received a quote from AJ Pty Ltd to undertake the works, for $281,942.40. Other quotes have outlined figures of $278,290.64 (from AK Company), and $364,135.77 (from AL Pty Ltd), both excluding non-urgent items. The husband opined that the cost might be $500,000, which included maintenance works as now necessary.
The husband engaged in considerable and costly litigation during the parties’ cohabitation. He estimates that he has spent close to $10 million in legal costs over time. His evidence was, “I have been in litigation for 45 years.”
The wife had savings of approximately $20,000 at trial, and no income. The husband has a significant monthly income, and significant expenses, which he has the capacity to reduce by a further sale of his assets.
The husband’s plant and equipment on the G Street property needs to be removed by the husband as a matter of justice and equity. The husband has known for a very long time that the wife seeks the orderly removal of these items from the G Street property by the husband or an agent of the husband. The husband had, until trial, refused to engage in that process, not because of the existence of the intervention order which would have limited his access to the property (but not that of an agent of the husband), but because for the husband, as he acknowledged, it is free and already available land in relation to which he needs to make no other arrangements nor any ongoing payments of rental.
The husband has had ample time to arrange for a sale and/or removal of his plant and equipment He has failed to do so. The Court shall make orders that the husband remove his plant and equipment within 60 days and, in the event, he does not do so, the wife can sell such plant and equipment on the G Street property, with her to have the conduct of the sale, including engaging any persons necessary to achieve a sale outcome. The wife can account to the husband in respect of the sale, and the sale costs and, as a condition of the sale, the wife may receive some part of the net proceeds, being 20 per cent, to account for the work needing to be done by her to carry out the sale.
The conduct of any sale on the G Street property will severely inconvenience the wife and cause her some considerable stress and expenditure of time. There will be required to be multiple people on her property to inspect the plant and equipment and to arrange for the removal of same after a successful sale.
The husband sought an order that the wife provide to him his wine collection and dining table, both of which are situate at the G Street property. The wife is content to provide the husband with his wine collection. She objects to the husband’s ownership and possession of the dining table. Neither party provided any evidence as to the previous history and/or ownership of this table. The husband simply submitted, through his counsel, that he wished for such table to be given to him with the wife submitting through her counsel that she objected to that course, and would not give the table to him. In these circumstances, it is not possible for the Court to determine either party’s priority to ownership of this piece of furniture, or what might be just and equitable as between them on specific evidence. The table having remained in the home of the wife since 2023, and the husband having ongoing access to greater financial resources than the wife, the Court determines that the appropriate, just and equitable outcome is to leave the table in the possession of the wife.
